<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-746-146  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 746 146.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  July 11 1990 n1516 p27(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Working the graveyard shift. (working conditions for women in theAsian electronics sector)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rosier, Mechtild.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Women make up 90 percent of the personnel in Asian electronicscompanies.andP;  They work in shifts, sleep in shifts and have veryhigh production targets.andP;  If they do not meet their quota theymust make it up in unpaid overtime.andP;  Health hazards, such asworking with chemicals and long work hours, are taking their toll.andO;The night-shift is popular because workers actually get paid forovertime; ten to 16-hour days are common.andP;  Basic wages average 80pounds sterling per month.andP;  Some companies pay bonuses for goodperformance, and provide free meals, transportation and medicalcare.andP;  Most workers have had 12 years of education.andP;  Most womenwork without a legal contract and the trend is toward hiring on atemporary basis.andP;  Unions are stifled, it is against the law toform unions in Malaysia and countries like Thailand and Hong Konguse management tactics and job insecurity to control unionactivity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     WomenEmploymentElectronicsIndustry AnalysisMalaysiaHong KongThailandWork HoursWork EnvironmentHuman Factors.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>